@comment *********************************************************************
@comment ** 5.2.1 File/Sort-Description                                     **
@comment *********************************************************************
@page
@newsubsection{5.2.1,File/Sort-Description}
@diagram{File/Sort-Description,DD-FD-SD,DD-FD-SD,DD-FD-SD}@enumerate
@p @item The reserved words @syntax{ARE}, @syntax{AT}, @syntax{CHARACTERS} (@syntax{RECORD} clause only), @syntax{CONTAINS}, @syntax{FROM}, @syntax{IN}, @syntax{IS}, @syntax{ON} and @syntax{WITH} are optional and may be included, or not, at the discretion of the programmer.  The presence or absence of these words has no effect upon the program.
@p @item The terms @syntax{RECORD IS} and @syntax{RECORDS ARE} are interchangeable.
@p @item The terms @syntax{REPORT IS} and @syntax{REPORTS ARE} are interchangeable.
@p @item Only files intended for use as work files for either the @syntaxref{SORT} or @syntaxref{MERGE} statements should be coded with an SD --- all others should be defined with a FD.
@p @item The sequence in which files are defined via @syntax{FD} or @syntax{SD}, as compared to the sequence in which their @syntax{SELECT} statements were coded, is irrelevant.
@p @item  The name specified as @term{file-name-1} must exactly match the name specified on the file's @syntax{SELECT} statement.
@p @item The @syntaxidx{CODE-SET} clause allows a custom alphabet, defined in the @syntaxref{SPECIAL-NAMES} paragraph, to be associated with a file. This clause is valid only when used with sequential or line sequential files.
@p @item The @syntax{LINAGE} clause may only be specified in the @syntax{FD} of a sequential or line sequential file.  If used with a sequential file, the organization of that file will be implicitly changed to line sequential.   The various components of the @syntax{LINAGE} clause define the layout of printed pages as follows:
@itemize @bullet
@p @item @syntaxidx{LINES AT TOP} --- the number of unused (i.e. left blank) lines at the top of every page.  The default if this if not specified is zero.
@p @item @syntaxidx{LINES AT BOTTOM} --- the number of unused (i.e. left blank) lines at the bottom of every page.  The default if this if not specified is zero.
@p @item @syntaxidx{LINAGE IS n LINES} --- the total number of used/usable lines on the page.
@p @item The sum of the previous three specifications should be the total number of possible lines available on one printed page.
@p @item @syntaxidx{FOOTING AT} --- the line number beyond which nothing may be printed except for any footing that is to appear on every page.  The default for this if not specified is zero, meaning there will be no footings.  This value cannot be larger than the @syntax{LINAGE IS n LINES} value.
@end itemize
@item This page structure --- once defined --- can be automatically enforced by the @statementref{WRITE}.
@p @item Specifying a @syntax{LINAGE} clause in an @syntax{FD} will cause the @register{LINAGE-COUNTER} to be created for the file.  This automatically-created data item will always contain the current relative line number on the page being prepared which will serve as the starting point for a @statement{WRITE}.
@p @item  The @syntaxidx{RECORD CONTAINS} and @syntaxidx{RECORD IS VARYING} clauses are ignored (with a warning message issued) when used with line sequential files.  With other file organizations, these mutually-exclusive clauses define the length of data records within the file.  The data item specified as @term{identifier-6} must be defined within one of the record descriptions of @term{file-name-1}.
@p @item The @syntaxidx{REPORT IS} clause announces to the compiler that the file will be dedicated to the Report Writer Control System (RWCS); the clause names one or more reports, each to be described in the report section.  The following special rules apply when the @syntax{REPORT} clause is used:
@enumerate A
@p @item The clause may only be specified in the @syntax{FD} of a sequential or line sequential file.  If used with a sequential file, the organization of that file will be implicitly changed to line sequential.
@p @item The @syntax{FD} cannot be followed by record descriptions --- detailed descriptions of data to be printed to the file will be defined in the @syntaxref{REPORT SECTION}.
@p @item If a @syntax{LINAGE} clause is also specified, Values specified for @syntax{LINAGE IS} and @syntax{FOOTING AT} will be ignored.  The values of @syntax{LINES AT BOTTOM} and @syntax{LINES AT TOP}, if any, will be honored.
@end enumerate
@item The following special rules apply only to sort/merge work files:
@enumerate A
@p @item Sort/merge work files should be assigned to @syntax{DISK} (or @syntax{DISC}) on their @syntax{SELECT} statements.
@p @item Sorts and merges will be performed in memory, if the amount of data being sorted allows.
@p @item Should actual disk work files be necessary due to the amount of data being sorted or merged, they will be automatically allocated to disk in a folder defined by:
@itemize @bullet
@p @item The @envvarruntimeref{TMPDIR}
@p @item The @envvarruntime{TMP}
@p @item The @envvarruntime{TEMP}
@end itemize
@* (in that order)
@p @item These disk files will be automatically purged upon @syntax{SORT} or @syntax{MERGE} termination.  They will also be purged if the program terminates abnormally before the @syntax{SORT} or @syntax{MERGE} finishes.  Should you ever need to know, temporary sort/merge work files will be named "cob*.tmp".
@p @item If you specify a specific filename in the sort/merge work file's @syntax{SELECT}, it will be ignored.
@end enumerate
@item @xref{Data Description Clauses}, for information on the @syntax{EXTERNAL} and @syntax{GLOBAL} options.
@end enumerate
