@newsection{5.7,SCREEN SECTION}
@diagram{SCREEN-SECTION-Data-Item,DD-SS-Data-Item,DD-SS-Data-Item,None}@p The screen section describes the screens to be displayed during terminal/console I-O.
@enumerate
@p @item The reserved words @syntax{CHARACTER} (@syntax{SEPARATE} clause), @syntax{IS}, @syntax{NUMBER}, @syntax{RIGHT}, @syntax{TIMES} and @syntax{WHEN} are optional and may be included, or not, at the discretion of the programmer.  The presence or absence of these words has no effect upon the program.
@p @item The reserved word @syntax{COLUMN} may be abbreviated as @syntax{COL}.
@p @item The reserved word @syntax{PICTURE} may be abbreviated as @syntax{PIC}.
@p @item The following sets of reserved words are interchangeable:
@itemize @bullet
@p @item @syntax{AUTO}, @syntax{AUTO-SKIP} and @syntax{AUTOTERMINATE}
@p @item @syntax{BACKGROUND-COLOR} and @syntax{BACKGROUND-COLOUR}
@p @item @syntax{BELL} and @syntax{BEEP}
@p @item @syntax{FOREGROUND-COLOR} and @syntax{FOREGROUND-COLOUR}
@p @item @syntax{FULL} and @syntax{LENGTH-CHECK}
@p @item @syntax{REQUIRED} and @syntax{EMPTY-CHECK}
@p @item @syntax{SECURE} and @syntax{NO-ECHO}
@end itemize
@item Data items defined in the screen section describe input, output or combination screen layouts to be used with @statementref{ACCEPT screen-data-item} or @statementref{DISPLAY screen-data-item} statements.  These screen layouts may define the entire available screen area or any subset of it.
@p @item The term 'available screen area' is a nebulous one in those environments where command-line shell sessions are invoked within a graphical user-interface environment, as will be the case on Windows, OSX and most Unix/Linux systems --- these environments allow command-line session windows to exist with a variable number of available screen rows and columns.  When you are designing GNU COBOL screens, you need to do so with an awareness of the logical screen row/column geometry the program will be executing within.
@p @item Data items with level numbers 01 (Constants), 66, 78 and 88 may be used in the screen section;  they have the same syntax, rules and usage as they do in the other data division sections.
@p @item Without @syntaxref{LINE} or @syntaxref{COLUMN} clauses, screen section fields will display on the console window beginning at whatever line/column coordinate is stated or implied by the @syntax{ACCEPT screen-data-item} or @statement{DISPLAY screen-data-item} that presents the screen item.  After a field is presented to the console window, the next field will be presented immediately following that field.
@p @item A @syntax{LINE} clause explicitly stated in the definition of a screen section data item will override any @syntax{LINE} clause included on the @syntax{ACCEPT screen-data-item} or @statement{DISPLAY screen-data-item} that presents that data item to the screen.  The same is true of @syntax{COLUMN} clauses.
@p @item The Tab and Back-Tab (Shift-Tab on most keyboards) keys will position the cursor from field to field in the line/column sequence in which the fields occur on the screen at execution time, regardless of the sequence in which they were defined in the screen section.
@p @item @xref{Data Description Clauses}, for information on the usage of the various data description clauses.
@end enumerate
