@comment *********************************************************************
@comment ** 5.9.31 OCCURS                                                   **
@comment *********************************************************************
@page
@newsubsection{5.9.31,OCCURS}
@diagram{OCCURS (REPORT SECTION) Clause,DD-OCCURS-1,DD-OCCURS-1,None}
@diagram{OCCURS (SCREEN SECTION) Clause,DD-OCCURS-2,DD-OCCURS-2,None}
@diagram{OCCURS (All Other Sections Clause,DD-OCCURS-3,DD-OCCURS-3,None}
@center This syntax is valid in the following sections:
@center @strong{FILE}, @strong{WORKING-STORAGE}, @strong{LOCAL-STORAGE}, @strong{LINKAGE}, @strong{REPORT}, @strong{SCREEN}
@p The @syntax{OCCURS} clause is used to create a data structure called a table, where entries in that structure repeat multiple times.
@enumerate
@p @item The reserved words @syntax{BY} (INDEXED), @syntax{IS}, @syntax{KEY}, @syntax{ON} and @syntax{TIMES} are optional and may be included, or not, at the discretion of the programmer.  The presence or absence of these words has no effect upon the program.
@p @item The value of @term{integer-2} specifies how many entries will be allocated in the table.
@p @item The following is an example of how a table might be defined:
@p @example
05 QUARTERLY-REVENUE OCCURS 4 TIMES PIC 9(7)V99.
@end example
@* This will allocate the following:
@p @example
QUARTERLY-REVENUE(1)
QUARTERLY-REVENUE(2)
QUARTERLY-REVENUE(3)
QUARTERLY-REVENUE(4)
@end example
@* Each occurrence is referenced using the subscript syntax (a numeric literal, arithmetic expression or numeric identifier enclosed within parenthesis) shown above.
@p @item The @syntax{OCCURS} clause may be used at the group level too, in which case the entire group structure repeats, as follows:
@p @example
05 GRP OCCURS 3 TIMES.
    10 A     PIC X(1).
    10 B     PIC X(1).
    10 C     PIC X(1).
@end example
@* This would allow references to any of the following:
@p @example
GRP(1) - includes A(1), B(1) and C(1)
GRP(2) - includes A(2), B(2) and C(2)
GRP(3) - includes A(3), B(3) and C(3)
@end example
@* or each A,B,C item could be referenced as follows:
@p @example
A(1) - Character #1 of GRP(1)
B(1) - Character #2 of GRP(1)
C(1) - Character #3 of GRP(1)
A(2) - Character #1 of GRP(2)
B(2) - Character #2 of GRP(2)
C(2) - Character #3 of GRP(2)
A(3) - Character #1 of GRP(3)
B(3) - Character #2 of GRP(3)
C(3) - Character #3 of GRP(3)
@end example
@item The optional @syntaxidx{DEPENDING ON} clause can be added to an @syntax{OCCURS} to create a variable-length table.  In such cases, the value of @term{integer-1} specifies what the minimum number of entries in the table will be while @term{integer-2} specifies the maximum.  Such tables will be allocated out to the maximum size specified as @term{integer-2}.  At execution time the value of @term{identifier-1} will determine how many of the table elements are accessible.
@p @item See the documentation of the @syntaxref{SEARCH}, @syntaxref{SEARCH ALL} and @syntaxref{SORT} statements for explanations of the @syntaxidx{KEY} and @syntaxidx{INDEXED BY} clauses.
@p @item The @syntax{OCCURS} clause cannot be specified in a data description entry that has a level number of 01, 66, 77, or 88, although it is valid in data items described @i{subordinate} to an 01-level data item.
@p @item The following points apply to an @syntax{OCCURS} used in the report section:
@enumerate A
@p @item The optional @syntaxidx{STEP} clause defines an incrementation value that will be added to any absolute @syntaxref{LINE} or @syntaxref{COLUMN} number specifications that may be part of or subordinate to this data item's definition.
@p @item The optional @syntaxidx{VARYING} clause defines an identifier that may be used as a subscript for the multiple occurrences of this or any subordinate data item should the @syntaxref{SOURCE} or @syntaxref{SUM} clause(s) on this or subordinate data items reference entries within the table.  The @term{identifier-2} data item is dynamically created as needed and cannot be referenced outside the scope of the report data item definition.
@p @item The following two examples illustrate two different ways a report could include four quarters worth of sales figures in it's detail lines --- one doing things 'the hard way' and one using the advanced @syntax{OCCURS} capabilities of @syntax{STEP} and @syntax{VARYING}.  Both assume the definition of the following table exists in working-storage:
@p @center @t{05 SALES OCCURS 4 TIMES PIC 9(7)V99.}
@p First, the "Hard Way":
@p @example
10 COL 7  PIC $(7)9.99 SOURCE SALES(1).
10 COL 17 PIC $(7)9.99 SOURCE SALES(2).
10 COL 27 PIC $(7)9.99 SOURCE SALES(3).
10 COL 37 PIC $(7)9.99 SOURCE SALES(4).
@end example
@* And then using @syntax{STEP} and @syntax{VARYING}:
@p @example
10 COL 7  OCCURS 4 TIMES STEP 10 VARYING QTR FROM 1 BY 1
          PIC $(7)9.99 SOURCE SALES(QTR).
@end example
@end enumerate
@end enumerate
