@p @item @i{Without} the @syntaxidx{SEPARATE CHARACTER} option, the sign of the data item's value will be encoded by transforming the last (@syntaxidx{TRAILING}) or first (@syntaxidx{LEADING}) digit as follows:
@p @multitable @columnfractions .25 .25 .25
@headitem First/Last Digit @tab Value For Positive @tab Value for Negative
@item 0 @tab 0 @tab p
@item 1 @tab 1 @tab q
@item 2 @tab 2 @tab r
@item 3 @tab 3 @tab s
@item 4 @tab 4 @tab t
@item 5 @tab 5 @tab u
@item 6 @tab 6 @tab v
@item 7 @tab 7 @tab w
@item 8 @tab 8 @tab x
@item 9 @tab 9 @tab y
@end multitable
@p @item If the @syntax{SEPARATE CHARACTER} clause @i{is} used, then an actual @syntax{+} or @syntax{-} character will be inserted into the field's value as the first (@syntax{LEADING}) or last (@syntax{TRAILING}) character.  Note that having this character imbedded within the data item's storage does not prevent the data item from being used as a source field in arithmetic operations.
@p @item When @syntax{SEPARATE CHARACTER} is specified, the @syntax{S} symbol in the data item's @syntax{PICTURE} must be counted when determining the data item's size.
@p @item Neither the presence of an encoded digit (see above) nor an actual @syntax{+} or @syntax{-} character imbedded within the data item's storage prevents the data item from being used as a source field in arithmetic operations.
