@item Binary data (integer or floating-point) can be stored in either a @i{Big-Endian} or @i{Little-Endian} form.
@p Big-endian data allocation calls for the bytes that comprise a binary item to be allocated such that the least-significant byte is the right-most byte.  For example, a four-byte binary item having a value of decimal 20 would be big-endian allocated as 00000014 (shown in hexadecimal notation).
@p Little-endian data allocation calls for the bytes that comprise a binary item to be allocated such that the least-significant byte is the left-most byte.  For example, a four-byte binary item having a value of decimal 20 would be little-endian allocated as 14000000 (shown in hexadecimal notation).
@p All CPUs are capable of @syntax{understanding} big-endian format, which makes it the @syntax{most-compatible} form of binary storage across computer systems.
@p Some CPUs  such as the Intel/AMD i386/x64 architecture processors used in most Windows PCs  prefer to process binary data stored in a little-endian format.  Since that format is more efficient on those systems, it is referred to as the @syntax{native} binary format.
@p On a system supporting only one format of binary storage (generally, that would be big-endian), the terms 'most-efficient' and 'native format' are synonymous.
@p @item Data items that have the @syntaxidx{UNSIGNED} attribute explicitly coded, or @syntax{DISPLAY}, @syntax{PACKED-DECIMAL}, @syntax{COMP-5}, @syntax{COMP-X} items that do not have an @syntax{S} symbol in their picture clause cannot preserve negative values that may be stored into them.  Storing a negative value into such a field will actually result in the sign being stripped, essentially saving the absolute value in the data item.
@p @item Packed-decimal (i.e. @syntax{USAGE PACKED-DECIMAL}, @syntax{USAGE COMP-3} or @syntax{USAGE COMP-6}) data is stored as a series of bytes such that each byte contains two 4-bit fields, referred to as 'nibbles' (since they comprise half a "byte", they're just "nibbles" --- don't groan, I don't just make this stuff up!).  Each nibble represents a @syntax{9} in the @syntax{PICTURE} and each holds a single decimal digit encoded as its binary value (0 = 0000, 1 = 0001, @dots{} , 9 = 1001).
@p The @i{last} byte of a @syntax{PACKED-DECIMAL} or @syntax{COMP-3} data item will always have its left nibble corresponding to the last @syntax{9} in the @syntax{PICTURE} and its right nibble reserved as a sign indicator.  This sign indicator is always present regardless of whether or not the @syntax{PICTURE} included an @syntax{S} symbol.
@p The @i{first} byte of the data item will contain an unused left nibble if the @syntax{PICTURE} had an even number of @syntax{9} symbols in it.
@p The sign indicator will have a value of a hexadecimal A thru F.  Traditional packed decimal encoding rules call for hecadecimal values of F, A, C or E ("FACE") in the sign nibble to indicate a positive value and B or D to represent a negative value (hexadecimal digits 0-9 are undefined).  Testing with a Windows MinGW/GNU COBOL implementation shows that -- in fact -- hex digit D represents a negative number and any other hexadecimal digit denotes a positive number.  Therefore, a @syntax{PIC S9(3) COMP-3} packed-decimal field with a value of -15 would be stored internally as a hexadecimal 015D in GNU COBOL.
@p If you attempt to store a negative number into a packed decimal field that has no @syntax{S} in its @syntax{PICTURE}, the absolute value of the negative number will actually be stored.
@p @syntax{USAGE COMP-6} does not allow for negative values, therefore no sign nibble will be allocated.  A @syntax{USAGE COMP-6} data item containing an odd number of @syntax{9} symbols in its @syntax{PICTURE} will leave its leftmost nibble unused.
@p @item The @syntax{USAGE} specifications @syntax{FLOAT-DECIMAL-16} and @syntax{FLOAT-DECIMAL-34} will encode data using IEEE 754 @syntax{Decimal64} and @syntax{Decimal128} format, respectively.  The former allows for up to 16 digits of exact precision while the latter offers 34.  The phrase "exact precision" is used because the traditional binary renderings of decimal real numbers in a floating-point format (@syntax{FLOAT-LONG} and @syntax{FLOAT-SHORT}, for example) only yield an approximation of the actual value because many decimal fractions cannot be precisely rendered in binary.  The Decimal64 and Decimal128 renderings, however, render decimal real numbers in encoded decimal form in much the same way that @syntax{PACKED-DECIMAL} renders a decimal integer in digit-by-digit decimal form.  The exact manner in which this rendering is performed is complex (Wikipedia has an excellent article on the subject  just search for @syntax{Decimal64}).
@p @item GNU COBOL stores @syntax{FLOAT-DECIMAL-16} and @syntax{FLOAT-DECIMAL-34} data items using either Big-Endian or Little-Endian form, whichever is native to the system.
@p @item The @syntax{USAGE} specifications @syntax{FLOAT-LONG} and @syntax{FLOAT-SHORT} use the IEEE 754 @syntax{Binary64} and @syntax{Binary32} formats, respectively.  These are binary encodings of real decimal numbers, and as such cannot represent every possible value between the minimum and maximum values in the range for those usages.  Wikipedia has an excellent article on the Binary64 and Binary32 encoding schemes  just search on @syntax{Binary32} or @syntax{Binary64}.
@p GNU COBOL stores @syntax{FLOAT-LONG} and @syntax{FLOAT-SHORT} data items using either Big-Endian or Little-Endian form, whichever is native to the system.
@p @item A @syntax{USAGE} clause specified at the group item level will apply that @syntax{USAGE} to all subordinate data items, except those that themselves have a @syntax{USAGE} clause.
@p @item The only @syntax{USAGE} that is allowed in the report section is @syntax{USAGE DISPLAY}.
@end enumerate
