@center This syntax is valid in the following sections:
@center @strong{FILE}, @strong{WORKING-STORAGE}, @strong{LOCAL-STORAGE}, @strong{LINKAGE}, @strong{REPORT}, @strong{SCREEN}
@p The @syntax{VALUE} clause is used to define condition names or to assign values (at compilation time) to data items.
@enumerate
@p @item The reserved words @syntax{ARE} and @syntax{IS} are optional and may be included, or not, at the discretion of the programmer.  The presence or absence of these words has no effect upon the program.
@p @item This clause cannot be specified on the same data item as a @syntaxref{FROM}, @syntaxref{TO} or @syntaxref{USING} clause.
@p @item The following points apply to using the @syntax{VALUE} clause in the definition of a condition name:
@enumerate A
@p @item The clauses @syntax{VALUE IS} and @syntax{VALUES ARE} are interchangeable.
@p @item The reserved words @syntax{THRU} and @syntax{THROUGH} are interchangeable.
@p @item @xref{88-Level Data Items}, for a discussion of how this format of @syntax{VALUE} is used to create condition names.
@p @item @xref{Condition Names}, for a discussion of how condition names are used.
@end enumerate
@item  The following points apply to using the @syntax{VALUE} clause in the definition of any other data item:
@enumerate A
@p @item In this context, @syntax{VALUE} specifies an initial compilation-time value that will be assigned to the storage occupied by the data item in the program object code generated by the compiler.
@p @item The @syntax{VALUE} clause is ignored on @syntaxref{EXTERNAL} data items or on any data items defines as subordinate to an @syntax{EXTERNAL} data item.
@p @item This format of the @syntax{VALUE} clause may not be used anywhere in the description of an 01 item (or any of it's subordinate items) serving as an @syntax{FD} or @syntax{SD} record description.
@p @item If the optional @syntaxidx{ALL} clause is used, it may only be used with an alphanumeric literal value; the value will be repeated as needed to completely fill the data item.  Here are some examples with and without @syntax{ALL} (the symbol @i{b} denotes a space):
@p @example
PIC X(5) VALUE "A"      *> A@i{bbbb}
PIC X(5) VALUE ALL "A"  *> AAAAA
PIC 9(3) VALUE 1        *> 001
PIC 9(3) VALUE ALL "1"  *> 111
@end example
@item When used in the definition of a screen data item:
@enumerate a
@p @item A figurative constant may not be supplied as @term{literal-1}.
@p @item Any @syntaxref{FROM}, @syntaxref{TO} or @syntaxref{USING} clause in the same data item's definition will be ignored.
@p @item If there is no picture clause specified, the size of the screen data item will be the length of the @term{literal-1} value.
@p @item If there is no picture clause and the @syntax{ALL} option is specified, the @syntax{ALL} option will be ignored.
@end enumerate
@item Giving a table an initial, compile-time value is one of the trickier aspects of COBOL data definition.  There are basically three standard techniques and a fourth that people familiar with other COBOL implementations but new to GNU COBOL may find interesting.  So, here are the three @i{standard} approaches:
@enumerate a
@p @item Don't bother worrying about it at compile-time.  Use the @syntaxref{INITIALIZE} to initialize all data item occurrences in a table (at run-time) to their data-type-specific default values (numerics: 0, alphabetic and alphanumerics: spaces).
@p @item Initialize small tables at compile time by including a @syntax{VALUE} clause on the group item that serves as a parent to the table, as follows:
@p @example
05  SHIRT-SIZES          VALUE "S 14M 15L 16XL17".
    10 SHIRT-SIZE-TBL    OCCURS 4 TIMES.
       15 SST-SIZE       PIC X(2).
       15 SST-NECK       PIC 9(2).
@end example
@item Initialize tables of almost any size at compilation time by utilizing the @syntaxref{REDEFINES} clause:
@p @example
05  SHIRT-SIZE-VALUES.
    10 PIC X(4)          VALUE "S 14".
    10 PIC X(4)          VALUE "M 15".
    10 PIC X(4)          VALUE "L 16".
    10 PIC X(4)          VALUE @syntax{XL17}.
05  SHIRT-SIZES          REDEFINES SHIRT-SIZE-VALUES.
    10 SHIRT-SIZE-TBL    OCCURS 4 TIMES.
       15 SST-SIZE       PIC X(2).
       15 SST-NECK       PIC 9(2).
@end example
@* Admittedly, this table is much more verbose than the one shown with a group @syntax{VALUE}.  What is good about this initialization technique, however, is that you can have as many @syntax{FILLER} and @syntax{VALUE} items as you need for a larger table, and those values can be as long as necessary!
@end enumerate
@item Many COBOL compilers do not allow the use of @syntax{VALUE} and @syntaxref{OCCURS} on the same data item; additionally, they don't allow a @syntax{VALUE} clause on a data item subordinate to an @syntax{OCCURS}.  GNU COBOL, however, has neither of these restrictions!
@p Observe the following example, which illustrates a fourth manner in which tables may be initialized in GNU COBOL:
@p @example
05  X           OCCURS 6 TIMES.
    10 A        PIC X(1) VALUE '?'.
    10 B        PIC X(1) VALUE '%'.
    10 N        PIC 9(2) VALUE 10.
@end example
@* In this example, all six @syntax{A} items will be initialized to "?", all six @syntax{B} items will be initialized to "%" and all six @syntax{N} items will be initialized to 10.  It's not clear exactly how many times this sort of initialization will be useful, but it's there if you need it.
@end enumerate
@item The @syntaxref{FROM}, @syntaxref{TO}, @syntaxref{USING} and @syntax{VALUE} clauses are mutually-exclusive in any screen section data itsm's definition.
@end enumerate
